{{about||the television series|seaQuest DSV|other uses|SeaQuest (disambiguation)}} {{Italic title}} {{EngvarB|date=April 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}} The '''''Sea Quest''''' was a [[semi-submersible]] [[oil platform|drilling rig]]. She discovered the [[UK]]'s first [[North Sea oil]] on 14 September 1969 in the Arbroath Field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oilcity.co.uk/home/article.asp?pageid=471|title=Britain's Low Key First Success|last=Cresswell|first=Jeremy|date=25 September 2007|work=OilCity|accessdate=2009-06-20|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005011842/http://www.oilcity.co.uk/home/article.asp?pageid=471|archivedate=5 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=disasters/> She also discovered the first giant oil field named [[Forties Oil Field|Forties]] on 7 October 1970.<ref name=disasters> {{cite web | title = Sea Quest | publisher = oilrigdisasters.co.uk | url= http://home.versatel.nl/the_sims/rig/seaquest.htm | accessdate=2011-06-24}} </ref><ref name=giant> {{cite web |title = The First UK Giant Oil Field |first = Jane |last = Whaley |publisher = GeoPublishing |url = http://www.geoexpro.com/history/thefirstukoilfield/ |accessdate = 2011-06-25 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100726053210/http://www.geoexpro.com/history/thefirstukoilfield/ |archivedate = 26 July 2010 |df = dmy-all }} </ref>
The ''Sea Quest'' was built by [[Belfast]] [[shipbuilder]]s [[Harland and Wolff]] for [[BP]] at a cost of £3.5&nbsp;million and launched on 8 January 1966.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/01/08/archives/oildrilling-rig-launched-in-belfast-for-north-sea-use.html|title=Oil-Drilling Rig Launched In Belfast for North Sea Use|date=8 January 1966|newspaper=The New York Times|page=33|accessdate=2009-06-20}}</ref> The entire structure was {{convert|320|ft}} high and weighed 150,000 tons, including three legs each {{convert|35|ft}} in diameter and {{convert|160|ft}} long that could be partially filled with water to control the height of the platform above the sea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dHwQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZZMDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1310,530537|date=4 July 1966|newspaper=The Age|location=Melbourne, Australia|title=Photograph caption|page=4|accessdate=2009-06-20}}</ref><ref name="BP history">{{cite book | last1 = Ferrier | first1 = RW | last2 = Bamberg | first2 = JH | title = The History of the British Petroleum Company | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] | year = 1982 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LVC0VlPOJxEC&pg=PA201 | isbn = 978-0-521-78515-0 | pages = 200–203}}</ref>
In 1977, ''Sea Quest'' was sold to [[Sedco]] (now part of [[Transocean]]) and renamed ''Sedco 135C''.<ref name=disasters/><ref> {{cite news |url= https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/djreprints/access/72686096.html?dids=72686096:72686096&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Mar+18%2C+1977&author=&pub=Wall+Street+Journal&desc=Profit+of+British+Petroleum+Rose+In+Fourth+Period&pqatl=google |title= Profit of British Petroleum Rose In Fourth Period |date= 1977-03-18 |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=2011-06-24 |id = {{subscription required}}}} </ref> She was towed to the west coast of Africa. On 17 January 1980, while drilling in the Warri area, [[Nigeria]], a [[Blowout (well drilling)|blowout]] occurred and the rig sustained extensive fire damage. The rig was then deliberately sunk in deep water.<ref name=disasters/>
